					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Maybe someone else can chime in with better info, but myself I've always advised against using $2004 for writing because I've never seen any known-working program do that (not that I've looked extensively).  My early programs did that because I had so few sprites, but when I had them tested IIRC the sprites didn't all show up.  I've kinda wondered if $2003 is there only for internal use by the DMA, but I don't really have any understanding of why that would be.
<br />
<br />I know there was an interesting thread on here a while back about $2003/$2004, but I think it was mostly about tricks based on reading it for a kind of very hacky scanline detection.
<br />
<br />If you <em>really</em> need the extra RAM you can still use the DMA, but strategically use the inconsequential bytes of the buffer page (basically all of them except the tile #).  It'd be non-contiguous though.  I actually did that on my Hot Seat Harry game, it uses the zeropage for sprites and everything else!  That was entirely to make the program smaller, so it'd fit in 1kB.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

